defaultExecutive Summary
default&#xa0;
default1.  This submission outlines the work of ICEVI (the International Council for Education of People with Visual 
defaultImpairment) in promoting the education of visually impaired children and working to achieve a higher profile for disability in the post-2015 development framework.  It summarises my activity in relation to the UK Government on international development and
default concludes with a number of recommendations which 
defaultDfID
default should take on board going forward.
default&#xa0;
defaultIntroduction:
default&#xa0;
default2.  I am blind and President of ICEVI (The International Council for Education of People with Visual Impairment), a worldwide body dedicated to promo
defaultting quality education for visually impaired children.
default&#xa0;
default3.  It is estimated that there are 6 million children worldwide with a visual impairment, 80 % of them in developing countries.  Of these, over 90 % or 4
default,4
default million receive no education at all.  In 199
default0 the Education 
defaultFor
default All (EFA) programme was launched by the UN with the goal of universal access to primary education by 2015.  EFA has made significant progress in reaching non-disabled children, but it has to a large extent failed to include children wit
defaulth disabilities, particularly those that require alternative modes of communication.
default&#xa0;
default4.  For these reasons, in 2006, in conjunction with the World Blind Union (WBU), we launched the EFA-VI (Education for All Visually Impaired Children) initiative.  Since t
defaulthen, we have been instrumental in getting nearly 75,000 children into school, and have involved some 35,000 participants in capacity building programmes.  But we are conscious that to achieve our aim, we need to work with many partners and to persuade nati
defaultonal governments to accept their responsibility to see to it that visually impaired children go to school.
default&#xa0;
default5.  This background has led me to take an interest in the UK Government's stance on international development issues.
default&#xa0;
default6.  Earlier this year, with N
defaultGO support, I coordinated a group of Parliamentarians to make representations to the Prime Minister in his capacity of co-Chair of the Secretary-General's High 
defaultLevel Panel about the importance of disability featuring more prominently in the post-2015 devel
defaultopment framework.
default  It wasn't possible to arrange a meeting with the Prime Minister.  Our letter was referred to 
defaultDfID
default and I ended up meeting the PUSS, Lynne Featherstone, on behalf of the group at the end of October.
default&#xa0;
default7.  In the result we were very happy wi
defaultth the high profile given to disability throughout the High Level Panel's report, from the reference to "leave no-one behind", to the call for a "data revolution" or the disaggregation of data by disability and other factors, and the recommendation that "t
defaultargets will only be considered 'achieved' if they are met for all relevant income and social groups.  We understand that the Prime Minister's leadership was instrumental in securing this outcome.
default&#xa0;
default8.  ICEVI will continue to engage with the post-2015 proces
defaults, which has now moved to the Open Working Group.  The rest of this submission consists of the recommendations which we put to the PUSS.
default&#xa0;
defaultSubmission
default&#xa0;
default9.  Although disability has been a priority for the Coalition Government's international development work 
defaultfrom the first, my experience has been that, compared with gender equality, it has remained very much an after-thought.  When I began to address 
defaultDfID's
default international work, I found that 
defaultDfID's
default Guidelines on Disability were criticised.  Accordingly, after a 
defaultmeeting with PUSS Stephen O'Brien in June 2011, I arranged for a short note of key messages to be prepared which the Department circulated to country offices.
default This is appended as Annex 1 (below).
default&#xa0;
default10.  When I met 
defaultLynne
default Featherstone, I strongly welcomed the
default priority she was now giving to disability.
default&#xa0;
default11.  I said it was important to build on her "accessible schools" announcements in New York and Uganda with a broad interpretation of "accessible" to include educational materials, induction loops, etc.
default&#xa0;
default12.  Th
defaulte initiative should be expanded to embrace health - 
defaultDfID
default should not fund healthcare projects, e.g. secondary clinic and hospital construction projects which do not meet inclusion criteria.  Development projects should be looking at the development of the w
defaulthole child.
default&#xa0;
default13.  Disability needs to be embedded in all that 
defaultDfID
default does - the Department should adopt a systemic approach.  As a test case, the Department could ensure that a big upcoming funding decision, e.g. some bilateral reviews or a big multi-lateral
default review, is fully inclusive of disabled people.
default&#xa0;
default14.  The Department's Partnership Principles dating from 2005 make no reference to disability.  This should be remedied in the revision which is currently taking place.
default&#xa0;
default15.  Accountability mechanisms need t
defaulto be in place to monitor the effectiveness of work on disability.  The Department's particular interest in seeing that the right data are collected has been noted.  The UK could provide leadership globally on this issue, e.g. through a multi-stakeholder pa
defaultrtnership on the collection of disaggregated data in line of the High Level Panel's recommendation.
default&#xa0;
default16.  We cannot properly tackle poverty without tackling disability.  Optimal economic growth will not be achieved without the inclusion of disabled people.
default  The PUSS recognises that economic growth has to be inclusive growth.
default&#xa0;
default17.  It will be important to "lock in" the progress which is being made on disability and to see that accountability mechanisms and staff capacity remain in place.
default&#xa0;
defaultColin Low
