defaultAnnex default1default&#xa0;
defaultHow can DFID teams act on UK commitments to disability &amp; inclusive education?
default&#xa0;
defaultThe UK government is committed to education for people with disabilities, who form 15% of the population, and 30% of children out of 
defaultschool .
default This note offers actions which 
defaultDFID country teams can include in planning and day to day work.  More advice is available in DFID’s Guidance Note on Education for Children with Disabilities.
default&#xa0;
defaultSome general principles
default&#xa0;
defaultDFID’s influence goes well beyond the money it spends. Questions asked 
defaultby DFID will stimulate action from other donors, government and civil society. DFID staff can make a big difference by asking 1) which barriers affect disabled adults and children; 2) what is being done to improve their participation in education; 3) what 
defaultmore can be done. 
default&#xa0;
defaultDFID experts and programmes may already be making good progress. It is important to share this so that the UK government can show results against its commitments.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn low income countries there are often opportunities to help school sys
defaulttems build in inclusive approaches as they develop. 
defaultPrioritising these offers better value for money than waiting until systems are too fixed to change without greater effort and cost.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultA lack of data, or low visibility of disabled people, should not prev
defaultent progress. It is better to encourage parallel efforts which can grow together – work to get more people with disabilities into education, and efforts to develop evidence of results. 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultKey actions that can be included in the work of a DFID country team
default&#xa0;
defaultInclude in plans a narrative section on activities expected to improve participation of people with disabilities in education. 
defaultReport against these, including challenges.
default&#xa0;
defaultMake it clear that DFID expects disability to be reflected in Performance Framework
default Agreements for multilateral or bilateral funding. Ask other donors and government how the PFA can include results on people with disabilities, and how these can be captured. 
default&#xa0;
defaultMake a colleague DFID’s disability contact, and ask them to consult disabled pe
defaultople’s organisations a few times a year. Use information from this in ministerial discussions. 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultKey actions that can be included in the work of a DFID education advisor
default&#xa0;
defaultRequest that all logical frameworks for DFID-funded work managed by private sector, 
defaultcivil 
defaultsociety or multilateral agencies contain a gender-disaggregated indicator on how people with disabilities will be reached or benefited. 
default&#xa0;
defaultAsk for the design of teacher training curricula to prioritise helping teachers to welcome and work with a diverse range of learners. Advise that design teams include people with experience of working on disability in mainstream education. 
default&#xa0;
defaultAsk for disagg
defaultregated data on education access and outcomes for disabled children. If official sources are weak, NGOs, DPOs or universities often have data and advice. Advising on selection of EMIS
default or household survey contractors can ensure that organisations which wil
defaultl prioritise disability-disaggregated information are chosen.
